### compile & link phase
The directive link function is similar to the directive compile function, with two important differences:

1.  The two functions get called at different points in time. Directive compilation functions get 
called during compilation, and linking functions get called during linking. The difference is 
mostly relevant in terms of what other directives do during these two steps. For example, in the 
presence of DOM-altering directives like ngRepeat, your directive will get compiled once but 
linked separately for each repetition introduced by ngRepeat.
2.  The compile function has access to the DOM element and the Attributes object, as we have 
seen. The link function has access to not only these, but also the Scope object being linked to. 
This is often where application data and functionality gets attached to the directive.
